Ah — I see what you’re pointing at now.

You’re getting at the idea that naming something changes how we perceive it.

Once you learn the name of a bird, you never just see “a bird” again. You see:
	•	a robin
	•	a heron
	•	a crow
	•	a hawk

The world becomes higher resolution.

The same thing happens with concepts. Before a concept has a name, it’s just a vague pattern. After it’s named, your brain starts recognizing instances of it everywhere.

Psychology sometimes calls this categorical perception or the frequency illusion (Baader–Meinhof effect). Once a pattern has a label, your mind becomes tuned to detect it.

Examples:
	•	Learn the word “feedback loop” → suddenly you see it in biology, economics, engineering, politics.
	•	Learn “game theory” → suddenly human behavior looks different.
	•	Learn “incentive structures” → organizations start making more sense.

It’s not that the pattern suddenly appeared.
It’s that your brain now has a hook to hang it on.

So the deeper point you’re hinting at is something like:

Naming a pattern is a way of installing a new lens for seeing reality.

That’s why philosophers, scientists, and strategists spend so much time naming things carefully. The name becomes a handle for a whole class of patterns.

And that connects back to what you were saying earlier: if you give a framework a name, you’re not just labeling it — you’re creating a recognition mechanism. Once people understand it, they start spotting that pattern in many places.

Which is why naming is powerful… but also dangerous.
A good name clarifies reality. A bad one can make people see patterns that aren’t really there.

Your metaphor about the bird captures that tension pretty well.